name: Director Láº¹ykÃ¬Ã­
text: JAGUN JAGUN And THE CULTURE OF MISPLACED ACTIVISM.  I hardly watch movies.  But some how, I watched #JagunJagunMovie .  In the movie, while many are mesmerized with the custume, action and others, the only aspect that spoke to me is that part that I can simply describe misplaced activism.  So, what is misplaced activism?  In jagun jagun training camp, one of the soldiers, gbotija protested against the small portion of food, given to them by the agemo lady.  In his protest, he said the portion of food given to them was small, beyond the normal portion they are expected to get.   He therefore sent message of protest to agemo.  When gbotija protest reached agemo, she was infuriated and instantly went to the camp, in search of the protester.  While at the camp, Agemo asked for those who protested over the portion of food and gbotija confidently stepped forward, in the usual activist arrogance.  He spoke about the small food, which couldn't satisfy the soldiers and he emphasize that he's not scared to say the truth.  Naturally, he was punished.  In the mind of gbotija, he was being punished unjustly for speaking truth to power, but in the mind of agemo, she was being criticized irrationally for going extra mile to ensure the fighters get something to eat, no matter how little, while they are still sourcing for more food that would be sufficient at a later time.  After the punishment, Agemo had to educate Gbotija that the shortage of food was due to food scarcity, but she went extra mile to get what was supplied to the soldiers, pending when more food would be available.  She felt outraged that instead of being commended for going extra mile to provide for the soldiers amidst food scarcity, gbotija was protesting against her unjustly, claiming he was saying truth.  At the end of the day, Gbotija also realized that the person he was protesting against was actually the one who meant well.   He realized that the small portion of food from agemo, was actually a gesture from a concerned heart, not an attempt to starve the soldiers unduly.  When gbotija realized this, he apologized to agemo and they both became friends, then lovers.  The message here is actually for all of us, especially the activists.  We react to things as they appear, when in fact, they are much more to it.  Unfortunately, we don't really have the ability to seek the other side without casting aspersion, neither do we have the patience required to comprehend the whole situation.  We are quick to say we are saying truth or speaking truth to power, when infact, we may just be speaking out of ignorance, being unjust in the process.  We label people with all sorts of names, when in fact, they may probably be the best amongst us, or even better than us.  Our limited access to information, circumstance or insight, hinders our appreciation of the whole situation, but we are quick to react and jump into conclusion.  This is why some activists eventually turn friends with their former tyrant, when they eventually know them better, get to understand things better, like agemo and gbotija.  The other point is that, proactive communication may have prevented the problem in the first place.  This is why I have often maintained that Nigeria doesn't have any problem that communication couldn't solve. Communication is everything and with proactive communication, we could have averted many unnecessary situations.  If Agemo had communicated the food shortage ahead of time to the soldiers, when the small portion she struggled to get eventually came, they will appreciate her, not protest against her. But lack of adequate communication saw her efforts not appreciated.  My take away here is simple, we should move away from misplaced activism, to genuine collaborative approach to solving issues.  Those in authority should also know that, communication can solve all of our problems.  Written by: Abdulrazaq Hamzat  Profitable to direct in this era of Youthful exuberance!

name: T!O!M!ğŸ’ªğŸ» XPLUS
text: The storyline in #jagunjagunmovie  maybe enough for so many but for me, it can still be improved upon.  One thing I have realised from watching the few #Bollywood movies I have seen in recent times is the fact that they tend to aggrandize their culture.  For me, it's a good touch for @realfemiadebayo to specialise in making ONLY cultural yoruba movies and I applaud him for that (if that's what he's doing anyway) but one thing I really want him to work on is the use of real Yoruba stories as against fictional stories.  Yoruba is so rich in culture that @realfemiadebayo cannot run out of ORIGINAL YORUBA stories  in his next 100 movie attempts.  The likes of the stories of Timi of Ede, Sango, Basorun Gaa, Afonja, Orompoto, Ogun Idahomey, Kunrunmi, Fabunmi Oke-Imesi, latoosa, Ogedemgbe agbogun gboro, Ogun lakaaye, Esu Odara, Oranyan and so many others. These are stories of Yoruba heroes that needs to be told to compete with the likes of Thor, Iron man, Superman, Shiva, Bahuballi and the rest from around the world.  How we tell the story matters. Cultural aggarandization should be in view. We need to create the impression that our warriors are not just fat,pot-bellied people who are not skilled in acrobatics and hand to hand combat. We need to let the world know  that the Juju used by our fore fathers is so potent that it can rival the science of Iron man (even if we may not believe they work that way).  That is how to raise the awareness of the Yoruba culture and cultural heritage throughout the globe.  Mortal Kombat's scorpion character does a 'come over here'  trick but little did the world know that it exists in the Yoruba culture!  Even those things that don't exist, we can create and recreate in fight scenes.    In order to bring our history to cinema, we will need to get the facts of  original story right ( from custodians of culture and history, professors in the field, old men with good touch of the story etc), wash it as best as possible ( bring in minds in the cartoon industry, creative arts, acrobatics, hand to hand combat and gymnastics experts,  etc) and then recreate it INTO A BOLD STATEMENT ( actors' training, actors that fit each role, sound effects, serious directing works, cameras, lighting etc)   I know all of these boils down to #Ogungunuso, but then, nollywood movies need to move to the investment page of our economy, infact, an FDI attracting part of our economy!  Thank you

text: But there was a familiar feel around some scenes and acting. Bimbo's acting especially at that point Gbogunmi was killed.  Cue in Eleniyan's murder in #GangsofLagos and her epic scream...same vibe, just different settings. #JagunJagunMovie

name: Banky
text: The cast and crew of #JagunJagunMovie rock, no doubt. There was no cast out of place. Infact, surprises abound across casts. Bukunmi as Agemo/Kitan was beautiful, for one; Kola Ajeyemi as the pissed-off Prince was good, Faithia, Muyiwa Ademola were brilliant. #JagunJagunMovie

name: Banky
text: Agesinkole had one end scene that was all preachy and came across as moralistic. #JagunJagunMovie is same. @realfemiadebayo is literally preaching to the youths to avoid being tools in the hands of the political class. As an SSA at some point himself, is he telling us something?

name: Banky
text: For anyone that's seen Agesinkole before this, @realfemiadebayo is beginning to have a template for his movies. While this is not a bad thing, it begins to give off a vibe that is at once a dent in his creative exertions as well as a cliche to his stories. #JagunJagunMovie

name: Banky
text: She gives some revelation as she dies. Gbotija carries her corpse home and thus began a fight of supremacy between Ogundiji and his loyalists and Gbotija's crew. As expected, Gbotija defeats the deadly Ogundiji and affirms his supremacy. #JagunJagunMovie

name: Banky
text: #JagunJagunMovie chronicles the story of a young man, Gbotija, whose village had been ruined in an invasion. In his quest to become a skilled warrior, he enrols at the famous Ogundiji Warriors Academy where his inate anger and warrior drive stands him out amongst trainees...

name: Banky
text: @realfemiadebayo's #JagunJagunMovie has been the talk of town since it dropped recently. And fairly so. The sheer PR strategy deployed around the movie pales that of his previous effort, Agesinkole and so, we all anticipated the epic movie. Was it epic? Well...
